      "rationale": "NIH predicted by CFD compared against bench measurements at all 5 operating points. Mean relative error 8.3%, maximum 12.7%, both within the pre-specified 15% acceptance band. Uncertainty intervals overlap at all points confirming statistical consistency."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/morrison/criteria/qoi-relevance-mrl2",
      "rationale": "Normalized index of hemolysis (NIH) and relative hemolysis index (RH) are the regulatory quantities of interest per FDA guidance. CFD outputs directly mapped to these metrics. Scalar shear stress integration used per Giersiepen power-law model, consistent with predicate submissions."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/morrison/criteria/validation-relevance-mrl2",
      "rationale": "Validation experiments used the same FDA generic centrifugal pump geometry, identical blood analog fluid, and the same 5 flow-speed operating points as the COU. Validation domain directly overlaps COU domain. No extrapolation beyond validated conditions is required for the intended decision."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Numerical solver error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "not-applicable",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/morrison/criteria/solver-error-na",
      "rationale": "Not applicable at MRL 2 for this COU. Numerical solver error as a distinct factor from discretization error addresses iterative convergence and round-off in research-grade or in-house solvers. ANSYS Fluent is a commercially validated solver; iterative convergence is monitored via residual drop to 1e-6 and mass-imbalance < 0.01%, which is subsumed within the Software Quality Assurance and Discretization Error factors already assessed. Separate treatment of solver error is not required at MRL 2 per ASME V&V 40 Table 1 guidance."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Use error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "not-applicable",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/morrison/criteria/use-error-na",
      "rationale": "Not applicable at MRL 2. Use error as a standalone credibility factor applies when the simulation is operated by end-users with limited training or when the model is deployed in a clinical decision-support context. In this COU the model is executed exclusively by the developing engineering team under a documented simulation governance procedure. User qualification is captured under the SQA factor. Separate use-error assessment is not required at MRL 2 for an internal engineering analysis tool."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model form",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "not-applicable",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/morrison/criteria/model-form-na",
      "rationale": "Not applicable as a separate factor at MRL 2 for this COU. Model form uncertainty — including turbulence closure selection and constitutive law choice — is addressed implicitly through the Output Comparison and Validation Relevance factors, which demonstrate acceptable agreement between CFD predictions and experimental data across the full operating envelope. At MRL 2, explicit model-form uncertainty quantification (e.g., Bayesian model averaging across turbulence models) is not required. The SST k-omega model is the consensus choice for internal rotating flows per published benchmarks."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model inputs",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "not-applicable",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/morrison/criteria/model-inputs-na",
      "rationale": "Not applicable as a separate credibility factor at MRL 2. Model inputs (fluid viscosity, density, pump geometry tolerances) are well-characterized from supplier data sheets and ISO 10993-compliant fluid characterization. Sensitivity of NIH to input variation is low based on published literature for this pump class. Formal probabilistic uncertainty propagation through model inputs is not required at MRL 2; input uncertainty is bounded and documented in the test conditions factor."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test samples",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "not-applicable",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/morrison/criteria/test-samples-na",
      "rationale": "Not applicable at MRL 2. Test samples as a distinct factor addresses variability across multiple physical specimens (e.g., device-to-device manufacturing variation in a population study). This COU uses a single reference geometry (FDA generic centrifugal pump) with tightly controlled manufacturing tolerances. Sample variability is not a driver of model credibility for this single-device, single-geometry assessment. Statistical characterization of sample populations is appropriate at MRL 3 and above."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Equivalency of input parameters",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "not-applicable",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/morrison/criteria/equivalency-inputs-na",
      "rationale": "Not applicable at MRL 2. Equivalency of input parameters is relevant when validation experiments are conducted under conditions that differ from COU conditions, requiring formal bridging analysis. In this assessment the validation experiments were conducted under conditions directly matching the COU (same geometry, same fluid, same operating points). No parameter-space extrapolation or equivalency mapping is required. The Test Conditions factor documents the direct correspondence between validation and COU conditions."
    }
  ],
  "hasWeakener": [],
  "hasDecisionRecord": {
    "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/decision/cou1-cpb-accepted-2026",
    "type": "DecisionRecord",
    "actor": "https://uofa.net/morrison/actor/credibility-assessment-team",
    "role": "Credibility assessment team",
    "outcome": "Accepted",
    "rationale": "The credibility assessment for COU1 (CFD hemolysis prediction for Class II CPB device at MRL 2) is accepted based on the following structured evidence: (1) Seven credibility factors were assessed and all achieved levels meet or exceed required levels for MRL 2 — Software QA (achieved 2, required 1), Numerical Code Verification (achieved 2, required 1), Discretization Error (achieved 3, required 2), Test Conditions (achieved 2, required 2), Output Comparison (achieved 2, required 2), QOI Relevance (achieved 2, required 2), and Validation Relevance (achieved 2, required 2). (2) Six factors — Numerical Solver Error, Use Error, Model Form, Model Inputs, Test Samples, and Equivalency of Input Parameters — are documented as not-applicable at MRL 2 with explicit rationale grounded in ASME V&V 40 Table 1 scope criteria. Each not-applicable determination reflects a defensible engineering judgment: either the factor is subsumed within an assessed factor, the COU conditions directly match validation conditions eliminating the need for bridging, or the MRL 2 threshold does not require standalone treatment of the factor. (3) Validation results demonstrate CFD-predicted NIH within 8.3% mean relative error of bench measurements across all 5 operating points, within the pre-specified 15% acceptance band, with overlapping uncertainty intervals. Mesh convergence GCI < 3.2% confirms numerical adequacy. (4) The provenance chain from foundational experimental data through validation activities to this UoA is complete and traceable. No weakeners were identified. The model is fit for the intended purpose of identifying worst-case hemolysis operating conditions for regulatory submission.",
    "decidedAt": "2026-04-19T00:00:00Z"
  },
